[metadata]
title: Baserow: The Open Source Airtable Alternative You Can Self-Host
channel: @octopusinc_
source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HvdcfSlc8I4
upload_date: 20260611
transcript_source: captions
route: text

---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'ve ever used Airtable, you know the feeling. It starts as a friendly little spreadsheet, you build something genuinely useful on it, your whole team comes to depend on it, and then you hit the pricing tiers, the per seat cost, and the slightly uncomfortable realization that all of your data lives'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on someone else\'s servers. Baserow is the open source answer to exactly that problem. It\'s a no-code database and collaboration platform. Think spreadsheets that are secretly powerful databases that you can run in'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the cloud or host entirely on your own infrastructure. Same intuitive interface, same powerful features, but with full ownership of your data and no vendor lock-in whatsoever. Over the last few years, it\'s grown into'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one of the most popular open source Airtable alternatives anywhere, with more than 200,000 active users and a serious feature set. Let\'s take a look at what it can actually do and why so many teams are switching to it. At its heart, Baserow'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looks like a spreadsheet, and that is completely intentional. Anyone who can use a spreadsheet can be productive in it within minutes with zero training. But underneath that familiar grid is a real relational database. You get proper'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'field types, text, numbers, dates, single and multiple select, file attachments, and links between tables. So, your data actually has structure instead of being a pile of loosely typed'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cells that fall apart the moment someone fat-fingers an entry. And you\'re never stuck looking at your data just one way. The exact same records can be shown as a classic grid, a gallery of cards, a Kanban board, a calendar, or a timeline,'

[01:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you can spin up a form or a survey to collect new entries from anyone. Change the view and the underlying data stays exactly the same. That flexibility is what makes it click for whole teams. The marketing team'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lives in a calendar, the developers work a Kanban board, and everyone is pulling from the same single source of truth. Here is where Baserow really separates itself from the close alternatives. You can run the entire thing yourself with a'

[01:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'single command. Baserow ships as a Docker image, so spinning up your own private instance is genuinely one line in a terminal. Point it at a volume so your data persists, open up the port, and a minute later you have a full'

[02:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Baserow server running on your own machine or your own cloud. No subscription, no seat limits, and no data ever leaving your control. If you would rather not manage any infrastructure, there is a polished'

[02:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hosted cloud version, too. But the self-host option is always there, and it is the real complete product, not a crippled demo designed to push you toward a paid plan. For anyone who cares about data ownership, privacy,'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'regulatory requirements, or simply not being surprised by a bill at the end of the month, that combination of a genuinely good product and true no-asterisks self-hosting is the entire pitch. And Baserow has grown into a'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whole lot more than just a database. On top of your tables, you can use the application builder to create real web apps and customer portals. Drag-and-drop interfaces backed by your data, published on your own custom domain, all'

[02:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'without writing a line of code. There is a visual automations engine for wiring up workflows. When a row changes, send an email, hit a webhook, or update another table with full audit logs of everything that ran.'

[03:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can build dashboards to visualize your data with charts and metrics for the people who just need the summary. And there is Baserow AI, an assistant called Kuma, that can spin up an entire database structure from a plain English'

[03:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'description of what you\'re trying to build. So, it is not just storing your data anymore, it is helping you build the apps, the automations, and the reporting around it. It has quietly become a full no-code'

[03:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'platform that happens to have a genuinely great database sitting at its core. So, how does it actually stack up against Airtable, the tool most people are coming from? On the surface, the experience is'

[03:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'strikingly similar. The grids, the views, the field types, all feel immediately familiar, so the switch barely has a learning curve. The real differences are underneath. Airtable is proprietary and cloud-only.'

[04:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Your data lives on their servers, and the pricing scales with every seat and every record you add. Baserow is open source under the MIT license, which means you can self-host it for free, keep your data entirely on'

[04:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your own infrastructure, and scale without per-seat costs slowly eating you alive. You also get things Airtable simply will not hand you, full access to the underlying database, the ability to'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'write your own front-end and back-end plugins, and no risk of the rug being pulled if their pricing or terms change next quarter. If you value control and ownership, the math tips pretty hard toward the open option. Let\'s put some numbers on it.'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Baserow is built on a rock-solid, boring in the best way stack, a Python and Django back-end, a Vue.js front-end, and PostgreSQL underneath, which is exactly what you want holding your important'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data. The core platform is open source under the permissive MIT license. It has crossed 200,000 active users, picked up thousands of stars on GitHub, and it ships updates constantly, sitting at'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'version 2.2 as of this recording. And for the teams that need it, the cloud offering carries serious compliance credentials. GDPR, HIPAA, and SOC 2 Type 2, which is genuinely rare to see paired with a'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fully self-hostable open source core. You get the trust signals enterprises demand without giving up the freedom that drew you to open source in the first place. Now, the honest part, because it matters for making an'

[05:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'informed choice. Baserow uses what\'s called an open core model. The core platform is genuinely open source under the MIT license, and you can self-host that core for free forever. That is not a trick, and it is not a time limited'

[05:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trial that quietly expires. But some of the more advanced premium and enterprise features, things like single sign-on, advanced permissions, and certain admin and support tooling live behind paid plans. That is a completely legitimate'

[05:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and very common way for open source companies to fund full-time development and it is worth understanding up front so you know exactly which features are free and which ones are not. For most individuals and small teams,'

[06:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the open core genuinely does everything you need. For larger organizations, you\'re essentially choosing between paying for the pre- premium features or self-hosting the core and adding what you need yourself. Go in with your eyes'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open and it is a really fair deal. Baserow is one of the clearest wins in open source right now. Take a category-defining proprietary tool, rebuild it as something you can actually own, and then push it further with apps,'

[06:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automations, and AI layered on top. Whether you are an individual who just wants a powerful personal database or a team that is tired of per seat pricing and wants its data back, it is'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absolutely worth spinning up. The cloud version takes about 30 seconds to try and the self-hosted version is one Docker command away. The repository and the website are both linked down in the description. And if you enjoyed this'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breakdown, consider subscribing. We cover a new open source project worth knowing every single week. Thanks for watching and we will see you in the next one.'
